The '''Doak Walker Award''' honors the top [[running back]] in [[college football]] in the United States. Established in 1990, it is named in honor of [[Doak Walker]], a former running back who played for the [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU Mustangs]] from 1945 to 1949 and in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Detroit Lions]] from 1950 to 1955. The player is selected by the award's National Selection Committee, which consists of notable sportswriters, television commentators, analysts, radio sports personalities and former All-America and NFL All-Pro football players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/DoakWalkerAward/AboutUs/SelectionCommittee|title = Selection Committee - SMU}}</ref> Recipients receive a bronze sculpture of Doak Walker, designed by artist [[Blair Buswell]]. The most recent winner of the award was [[Jeremiyah Love]] of Notre Dame.

==Notable accomplishments==
[[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin Badgers]] running backs won four times in eight years from 2012 to 2019. The Badgers and [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]] are tied with the most wins with five apiece.<ref name=":0"/>

[[Ricky Williams]] from Texas (1997, 1998), [[Darren McFadden]] from the [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas Razorbacks]] (2006, 2007) and [[Jonathan Taylor (American football)|Jonathan Taylor]] from Wisconsin (2018, 2019) are the only three players to win the award twice.

